        "response": {
          "bodySize": 1738,
          "content": {
            "mimeType": "application/json",
            "size": 1738,
            "text": "{\"model\":\"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001\",\"id\":\"msg_01EsxEcBAQE2YcnTJByzQmmF\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"id\":\"toolu_01Nzzgj7UBzD39QNJwSZW7LD\",\"name\":\"extract-21\",\"input\":{\"text\":\"I love the concept! \\\"Podcast matchmaking\\\" is intriguing. But I need to dig deeper to find your real competitive edge.\\n\\nHelp me understand:\\n\\n1. **Who are you matching?** Are you connecting podcast hosts with guests? Podcasters with sponsors? Listeners with shows? Something else?\\n\\n2. **What problem does this solve?** What's the friction point you're removing? (e.g., hosts struggle to find quality guests, guests can't get on shows, sponsors can't find relevant podcasts?)\\n\\n3. **Why is your approach different?** What makes Friend of the Pod better than hosts just reaching out to people on Twitter, or using existing guest booking platforms?\\n\\nGive me the real story here—what's the insight that made you think \\\"this needs to exist\\\"?\",\"examples\":[\"We connect indie podcast hosts with subject matter experts who want media exposure, solving the problem that hosts waste hours vetting guests while experts don't know which shows to pitch.\",\"We match podcast sponsors with shows in their niche, using AI to analyze audience demographics so sponsors stop wasting money on irrelevant placements.\",\"We help listeners discover podcasts based on their interests by analyzing episode transcripts, solving the problem that podcast discovery is broken.\"]}}],\"stop_reason\":\"tool_use\",\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":2306,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":0,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":0,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":0},\"output_tokens\":317,\"service_tier\":\"standard\"}}"
